<p style=3D"color:#333"><small>By Trudi Roth</small></p>
<p style=3D"color:#333">A CEO client recently confessed to me, =E2=80=9CI=
=E2=80=99m so busy on back-to-back video calls that I don=E2=80=99t even ha=
ve time for a bathroom break.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"color:#333">That was no humblebrag. It was a clear, relatable i=
llustration of the dangers of over-accessibility, which research shows lead=
 to <a href=3D"https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmu7mwpvl4h6h07m3ef5/n2ho=
hqungpv4keu0/aHR0cHM6Ly9mdXJ0aGVyLm5ldC9iZWF0LWJ1cm5vdXQv" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color:#be8100" url-id=3D"1367386116">stress and burnout</a>. </p=
>
<p style=3D"color:#333">While multitasking is a hallmark of our digital age=
, it=E2=80=99s nothing new. Anyone with a busy job and personal life can lo=
se sight of the forest through the trees. </p>
<p style=3D"color:#333">Luckily, there=E2=80=99s a simple technique you can=
 use to overcome overwhelm pioneered by the legendary diplomat, author, tea=
cher, and businessman George P. Schultz, who recently passed away at 100.</=
p>
<p style=3D"color:#333">In the =E2=80=9980s, when he served as Reagan=E2=80=
=99s secretary of state, Schultz would shut the door of his office, grab a =
pen and paper, and declare himself unavailable for one hour. (Only the pres=
ident or his wife could interrupt.) In that small window, he made ample roo=
m to think big. </p>
<h4 style=3D"font-family:calluna, Georgia, serif;color:#111;font-size:22px;=
margin-bottom:0px;margin-top:30px">Daydream Believer</h4>
<p style=3D"color:#333">Schultz led a jam-packed life, notably holding four=
 cabinet-level positions under two presidents. Commanding respect from both=
 sides of the aisle, he tackled some of the greatest threats of our times, =
from nuclear proliferation to climate change.</p>
<p style=3D"color:#333">In 2017, <em>New York Times</em> journalist David L=
eonhardt shared Schultz=E2=80=99s secret sauce. As he recounts:</p>
<blockquote style=3D"background:#fafafa;color:#666;font-style:italic;margin=
-left:0;padding:20px 30px">Schultz told me that his hour of solitude was th=
e only way he could find time to think about the strategic aspects of his j=
ob. Otherwise, he would be constantly pulled into moment-to-moment tactical=
 issues, never able to focus on larger questions of the national interest. =
And the only way to do great work, in any field, is to find time to conside=
r the larger questions.</blockquote>
<p style=3D"color:#333">In other words, Schultz made space for purposeful d=
aydreaming. </p>
<p style=3D"color:#333">When your mind wanders, your mental <a href=3D"http=
s://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmu7mwpvl4h6h07m3ef5/48hvh7u09em3nwaq/aHR0cH=
